As an AI text model, I cannot directly render or display a 3D image. However, I can provide you with the **complete code** to generate a 3D house using **Three.js**, a popular JavaScript library for 3D graphics in the browser.

You can copy the code below, save it as an `.html` file (e.g., `house.html`), and open it in any modern web browser to see the rendered model.

### Three.js 3D House Generator

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>3D House Model</title>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; background-color: #87CEEB; }
        canvas { display: block; }
        #info {
            position: absolute;
            top: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            text-align: center;
            color: white;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-weight: bold;
            pointer-events: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="info">Click & Drag to Rotate | Scroll to Zoom</div>

    <!-- Load Three.js from CDN -->
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <!-- Load OrbitControls -->
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.128.0/examples/js/controls/OrbitControls.js"></script>

    <script>
        // 1. Scene Setup
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        scene.background = new THREE.Color(0x87CEEB); // Sky blue
        scene.fog = new THREE.Fog(0x87CEEB, 10, 50);

        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        camera.position.set(10, 10, 10);

        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ antialias: true });
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true;
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // 2. Controls
        const controls = new THREE.OrbitControls(camera, renderer.domElement);
        controls.enableDamping = true;

        // 3. Lighting
        const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0xffffff, 0.6);
        scene.add(ambientLight);

        const dirLight = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 0.8);
        dirLight.position.set(10, 20, 10);
        dirLight.castShadow = true;
        dirLight.shadow.mapSize.width = 2048;
        dirLight.shadow.mapSize.height = 2048;
        scene.add(dirLight);

        // 4. Materials
        const roofMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x8B4513, roughness: 0.9 });
        const wallMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0xFFFFFF, roughness: 0.5 });
        const doorMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x333333 });
        const windowMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x87CEEB, transparent: true, opacity: 0.6 });
        const grassMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x228B22 });

        // 5. Building the House
        const houseGroup = new THREE.Group();

        // --- Walls ---
        const wallGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(4, 4, 4);
        const walls = new THREE.Mesh(wallGeometry, wallMaterial);
        walls.castShadow = true;
        walls.receiveShadow = true;
        houseGroup.add(walls);

        // --- Roof ---
        const roofGeometry = new THREE.ConeGeometry(4, 3, 4);
        const roof = new THREE.Mesh(roofGeometry, roofMaterial);
        roof.position.y = 4; // Sit on top of walls
        roof.rotation.y = Math.PI / 4; // Rotate to align with walls
        roof.castShadow = true;
        houseGroup.add(roof);

        // --- Door ---
        const doorGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 2, 0.2);
        const door = new THREE.Mesh(doorGeometry, doorMaterial);
        door.position.set(0, 1, 2.1); // Front face, slightly inside
        houseGroup.add(door);

        // --- Windows ---
        const windowGeometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 1, 0.1);

        // Front Window
        const win1 = new THREE.Mesh(windowGeometry, windowMaterial);
        win1.position.set(0, 2, 2.05);
        houseGroup.add(win1);

        // Side Window
        const win2 = new THREE.Mesh(windowGeometry, windowMaterial);
        win2.position.set(2, 2, 0);
        win2.rotation.y = Math.PI / 2;
        houseGroup.add(win2);

        scene.add(houseGroup);

        // --- Ground (Grass) ---
        const groundGeometry = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100);
        const ground = new THREE.Mesh(groundGeometry, grassMaterial);
        ground.rotation.x = -Math.PI / 2;
        ground.receiveShadow = true;
        scene.add(ground);

        // 6. Animation Loop
        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);
            controls.update();
            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }

        // Handle Window Resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });

        animate();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to use this:
1.  **Copy** the code block above.
2.  Create a new file on your computer named `house.html`.
3.  **Paste** the code into that file and save it.
4.  **Double-click** `house.html` to open it in Chrome, Firefox, Safari, or Edge.

### What this code does:
*   **Scene Setup:** Initializes a 3D scene with a sky-blue background and fog.
*   **Lighting:** Adds ambient light (soft fill) and a directional light (sun) that casts shadows.
*   **Geometry Construction:**
    *   **Walls:** A white cube.
    *   **Roof:** A brown cone rotated to look like a pyramid roof.
    *   **Door & Windows:** Smaller boxes placed on the walls.
*   **Interaction:** Includes `OrbitControls`, allowing you to click and drag to rotate the camera around the house and scroll to zoom in/out.
